ce:section.ce:para:
A nanofluid consists of a two-phase system that includes both solid and liquid components. This system integrates metals, metal oxides, or other solid particles that exhibit enhanced thermal conductivity relative to water. These materials are present as nanometric particles (1–100 nm) suspended within a base fluid, such as water [7]. In 1995, during the annual meeting of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, Choi and Eastman [8] first introduced the concept of a nanofluid. Fluids demonstrate a markedly reduced thermal conductivity in comparison to solid materials. Utilizing fluids with suspended solid particles is a feasible approach for improving thermal conductivity. Their enhanced thermophysical properties and diverse applications across various industries, such as air conditioning, refrigeration, electronic cooling, heat exchangers, radiators, solar collectors, heat pipe manufacturing, and thermal storage systems, are leading to increasing attention [9,10]. Silver (Ag), copper (Cu), graphene oxide (GO), ferric oxide (FeO), carbon nanotubes (CNTs), and titanium oxide (TiO



                              2


                     ) are particles utilized as nanoparticles in solar panels.

